I’ve always wanted to build something from the ground up and detail exactly how I tackled any problems as I work through it. It provides a level of clarity and longevity, I’m able to understand mistakes in the past and journal it, serving as an immutable source of my progression. Therefore, I’ve decided to start with a fairly ambitious projection, one that would test my understanding of a program I use everyday and take for granted.
In this case I decided to build a database from scratch. At the current stage, this doesn’t mean too much to me and this article is not meant to hold any deeper knowledge than what the layman would understand when mentioning a database. After working with Postgres and other relational databases before, my naive understanding is a database consists of the following:
1 — Parser: This will be used to parse the query and store the results in a standard format
2 — Engine: Executes the instructions from the standard format
Here’s my attempt at implementing basic select functionality, albeit naively.
The Main Loop and Data storage
We will have out main loop that retrieves the user input, parses the query and executes the result. All results are simply printed to the console for the time being.
do {
std::string user_input {};
std::cout << "enter your SQL query here: ";
std::getline(std::cin >> std::ws, user_input);Parser parse(user_input);
Engine execute_instructions(parse.get_user_instructions());
} while (true)
Note that data is simply stored as a .csv file with hard coded columns and values.
As an aside:
I was recently watching this excellent video on memory management using Arenas by Ryan Fleury. The idea of frame arenas where you reserve virtual addresses at the beginning of the frame and clear the arena at the end was an interesting prospect and thought something similar could be implemented in the future here to deal with loading the file itself into memory.
The Parser
My implementation of the parser was creating a constructor that was linear and logical, the end goal was to populate the user instructions into a standard format. Everything related to the query itself is contained within the Query namespace and has the following form:
namespace Query
{
enum Type
{
q_select,
q_insert,
q_delete,
q_create,
q_drop,
number_of_queries,
}; enum Inequalities
{
equal,
not_equal,
less_than,
less_than_equal,
greater_than,
greater_than_equal,
};
struct Instructions
{
std::vector<std::string_view> select_column_names{};
std::string_view from_table_name{};
struct Conditions
{
std::string_view first_table_name {};
Inequalities inequality{equal};
std::string_view second_table_name {};
};
Conditions conditions{};
};
}
As you can see we detail different query types along with a standard format for storing user instructions. In this case, the standard format really only considers statements in the form
SELECT col1, col2 FROM table WHERE col1 ineq col2;Having this single namespace has been relatively helpful, my only concern is if we would like Instructions to be standard we either have to add different Instructions for each enumerator in Type or do something similar to factory or abstract factory design patterns (which I would like to avoid). I am leaning towards the former however I’m sure there are more appealing alternatives to this.
Now moving into the actual Parser class, here is the header file which may seem confusing at first however I break down each of the implementations below

class Parser
{
private:
std::string_view m_user_input{};
const Query::Type identify_query_type();
const std::string_view first_word();
Query::Instructions user_instructions; void parse_user_query(Query::Type query_type);
void select_parser();
Query::Inequalities inequality_to_enum(std::string_view inequality_substring);
template <typename T>
void populate_user_instructions(std::basic_string_view<T> token, Query::SelectParsing cur_parsing_area);
template <typename T>
std::vector<std::string_view> parse_in_select(std::basic_string_view<T> token);
template <typename T>
Query::Instructions::Conditions parse_in_conditions(std::basic_string_view<T> token);
public:
Parser(std::string_view user_input);
Query::Instructions get_user_instructions();
};
Firstly, I wanted our constructor to be linear, it has the form:
Parser::Parser(std::string_view user_input) : m_user_input(user_input)
{
const Query::Type query_type {identify_query_type()};
std::cout << "This is the query type " << query_type << "\n";
parse_user_query(query_type);
std::cout << "user query finished" << "\n";
}We first determine what type of query the user has input and then parse it. parse_user_query at face value seems relatively ambiguous and it has side effects such as modifying the private variable user_instructions. We could therefore either change the name to something more explicit -> populate_user_instructions which parses the users query for the means of modifying user_instructions.
identify_query_type is pretty self explanatory, retrieve the first word of the query and use that to determine the type of the query. In hindsight, this should probably be handled inside parse_user_query and performed dynamically as we parse the query.
lets look into parse_user_query a bit more,

void Parser::parse_user_query(Query::Type query_type)
{
switch (query_type)
{
case Query::q_select:
select_parser();
std::cout << "select parser finished";
break;
// case Query::q_insert: return insert_parser();
// case Query::q_delete: return delete_parser();
// case Query::q_create: return create_parser();
// case Query::q_drop: return drop_parser();
default: throw std::invalid_argument("Could not match query type");
}
}First we switch on the query type, select_parser then loops through the query itself

void Parser::select_parser()
/*
* Parses statements of the form
* SELECT star/(comma seperated column names)
* FROM table name
* WHERE condition;
*/
{
int cursor {0};
Query::SelectParsing cur_parsing_area {Query::in_select};
m_user_input = trim(m_user_input); while (cursor != std::string_view::npos)
{
cursor = m_user_input.find_first_not_of(" ", cursor);
auto end {m_user_input.find_first_of(" ", cursor)};
auto token {m_user_input.substr(cursor, end - cursor)};
cursor = end;
std::cout << "this is the main loop token - " << token << '\n';
if (token == "SELECT")
{
cur_parsing_area = Query::in_select;
end = m_user_input.find("FROM") - 1;
token = m_user_input.substr(cursor + 1, end - cursor);
std::cout << "detected select\n";
}
else if (token == "FROM")
{
cur_parsing_area = Query::in_from;
end = m_user_input.find("WHERE") - 1;
token = m_user_input.substr(cursor + 1, end - cursor);
std::cout << "detected from\n";
}
else if (token == "WHERE")
{
cur_parsing_area = Query::in_condition;
end = m_user_input.find(";");
token = m_user_input.substr(cursor + 1, end - cursor);
std::cout << "detected where\n";
}
else if (token == ";")
{
std::cout << "breaking main loop\n";
break;
}
std::cout << "this is the token " << token << '\n';
trim(token);
populate_user_instructions(token, cur_parsing_area);
cursor = end;
};
std::cout << "finish loop";
}
Ok, what this does it pretty simple. first we have two pointers, cursor and end along with token which retrieves the characters between cursor and end as a substring. An example of a single iteration of the loop:
SELECT col1, col2 FROM table WHERE col1 ineq col2;/*
cursor -> 0 (first whitespace is "S" since we trim the trailing and leading whitespace)
end -> 6 (points at whitespace between SELECT and col1)
token -> SELECT (note it doesn not include the whitespace)
enters SELECT branch:
end -> 19 (points at first letter in FROM)
token -> col1, col2 (note there is whitespace which is trimmed)
calls populate_user_instructions
*/
Our loop is pretty self explanatory and in hindsight we don’t need the while loop given what we want to search for is deterministic. I believe my approach should have consisted of an array of strings containing each of SELECT, FROM, WHERE etc instead of having a separate if conditional branch for each. This makes the parsing more predictable and easily extensible for future development.
populate_user_instructions then checks whether the parsing area is in any of the following:
template <typename T>
void Parser::populate_user_instructions(std::basic_string_view<T> token, Query::SelectParsing cur_parsing_area)
{
std::cout << "Entered populate user instructions \n";
if (cur_parsing_area == Query::in_select)
user_instructions.select_column_names = parse_in_select(token); else if (cur_parsing_area == Query::in_from)
user_instructions.from_table_name = trim(token);
else if (cur_parsing_area == Query::in_condition)
user_instructions.conditions = parse_in_conditions(token);
}
parse_in_select then just does the following
template <typename T>
std::vector<std::string_view> Parser::parse_in_select(std::basic_string_view<T> token)
{
std::vector<std::string_view> column_names(20);
int cursor {0};
std::string_view::size_type prev_end {std::string_view::npos};
while (cursor != std::string_view::npos)
{
auto end {token.find_first_of(",")};
if (end == prev_end) end = std::string_view::npos;
auto column {token.substr(cursor, end - cursor)};
column_names.push_back(static_cast<std::string_view>(trim(column))); if (end == std::string_view::npos) break;
cursor = end + 1;
prev_end = end;
};
return column_names;
}
Obviously there’s a couple of issues, first, column_names only reserves room for tables with 20 columns (it could make more sense to look at the first line of the table first in the FROM statement and reserve enough memory for that number of columns). Second, we don’t handle the wildcard *. The parsing strategy itself I believe is reasonable, we find where the comma occurs, find the values between the cursor position and the comma then modify the cursor position relative to the end (similar to the two pointer DSA questions you would see as a leetcode question).
the other two parsing methods for FROM and CONDITION are self explanatory and follow a similar approach except by using whitespaces as the delimiter.
For now that’s it with the Parser class, quite underwhelming however I’m hoping to make some improvements and I believe detailing my thoughts here have revealed the limitations of my current approach. Now to move onto the Engine.
The Engine
Our engine.h is provided below, I wouldn’t delve too much into what it does, we’ll go through my approach afterwards

class Engine
{
private:
QueryConditions implement_conds{};
void populate_select_columns(std::ifstream& table);
std::vector<std::string_view> parse_csv_line(std::string_view line);
std::vector<std::string_view> impose_inequality_condition(std::vector<std::string_view> columns);
void select_columns(std::vector<std::string_view> table_cols);
void print_row(std::vector<std::string_view> row_vals); Query::Instructions m_user_instructions {};
std::string retrieve_table_file_location();
const void display_table(std::ifstream& table);
std::string total_path {};
public:
Engine(Query::Instructions user_instructions);
};
First lets look at the constructor
Engine::Engine(Query::Instructions user_instructions)
: m_user_instructions {user_instructions}
{
std::ifstream table_output;
// simulates the from statement
table_output.open(retrieve_table_file_location(), std::ios::out | std::ios::in);
// simulates the select statement
populate_select_columns(table_output); display_table(table_output);
}
So we first open the table at the specified location. Then we populate the selects columns to keep in implement_conds which has the type of this struct
struct QueryConditions
{
std::vector<int> select_cols_to_keep{};
// std::unordered_map<std::string_view, int> select_cols_to_int{};
};hence, we keep the index of the columns we want to keep. For example, if our table has columns 1 to 4, and we only select col1 and col2 we keep the index [0, 1] in our vector.
